ALI:
Hi, we're a COGS 108 team at UCSD. Our project asks whether country-level caffeine consumption is associated with national health outcomes — specifically depression and all-cause mortality — after accounting for economic and lifestyle confounders. I'm Ali, and I'll walk through the motivation and setup.

[SLIDE: Research Question]
ALI:
Caffeine is one of the most widely consumed psychoactive substances on the planet. Most of the research linking caffeine to health outcomes operates at the individual level and within a single country. We wanted to ask a different question: do those patterns hold when you look across countries? And if you see a correlation, is it actually about caffeine, or is it just tracking wealth?
Our primary question is: across countries, is higher estimated caffeine intake associated with differences in depression burden or all-cause mortality? We also asked whether the dominant caffeine source matters — coffee versus tea — and whether any association survives controlling for GDP, smoking, and alcohol use.
This is an inference project. We're testing whether a relationship exists and quantifying how much of it survives confounder adjustment, not building a predictive model.

[SLIDE: Data + Methods]
BRANDON:
We built the dataset from seven sources. For caffeine exposure, we used per-capita coffee and tea consumption from World Population Review — 2023 for coffee, 2022 for tea — and converted those to an estimated daily caffeine intake in milligrams per person per day using standard caffeine-content conversion factors. From there, we labeled each country as coffee-dominant or tea-dominant based on which beverage contributed more by weight.
For outcomes, we used IHME GBD data for depression prevalence and all-cause mortality. For confounders, we pulled GDP per capita, smoking prevalence, and alcohol consumption from Our World in Data. All of this was merged into a country-year panel.
One upfront caveat: the caffeine exposure variable is a cross-sectional estimate applied to a multi-year panel. We're assuming national consumption patterns are relatively stable over time, which is a simplification.

[SLIDE: EDA — Trends and Distributions]
ANCHIT:
Before the regression, the EDA gave us two important things: a picture of the raw associations, and a clear view of the confounding structure.
On distributions: both coffee and tea consumption are right-skewed. A handful of Northern European countries consume far more than the global median, and the estimated caffeine variable inherits that skewness. We used medians and IQR throughout rather than means.
On trends: when we stratified outcome trends over time by caffeine tercile, countries in the highest caffeine group showed consistently lower all-cause mortality across the full panel. But immediately, the problem is obvious — these countries are also wealthier, and their better outcomes likely reflect healthcare systems and economic stability at least as much as caffeine.

[SLIDE: EDA — Confounder Structure]
CESAR:
The Spearman correlation heatmap makes the confounding structure explicit. GDP per capita correlates strongly with both caffeine intake and mortality. When we stratified the caffeine-mortality scatter by GDP tercile, the within-stratum association was visibly weaker than the overall pattern.
The caffeine-depression association was already weak in the EDA — less consistent across years, lower correlation coefficients, and it didn't survive the GDP stratification cleanly. That preview turned out to predict the regression results pretty well.

[SLIDE: Regression — Mortality]
ANCHIT:
We ran three OLS model specifications for each outcome — unadjusted, GDP-adjusted, and fully adjusted — on the most recent cross-section of 124 countries.
For mortality, the unadjusted model showed a strong negative association: a one-standard-deviation increase in estimated caffeine was associated with about 99 fewer deaths per 100,000, and that was highly significant with a p-value of 0.0009. But the model R-squared was only 0.087, meaning caffeine alone explains less than 9% of the cross-country variation in mortality.
Once we added log GDP per capita in Model 2, that caffeine coefficient dropped by 62.5% — from negative 99 down to negative 37 — and the model R-squared jumped to 0.608. GDP is doing almost all of the explanatory work. In the fully adjusted model adding smoking and alcohol, the caffeine coefficient barely moved, landing at negative 34.8 with a p-value of 0.057. The model R-squared reached 0.678. So caffeine falls just outside conventional significance after full adjustment, and GDP remains the dominant predictor by a wide margin — its coefficient is over seven times larger than caffeine's.

[SLIDE: Regression — Depression]
CESAR:
For depression, the story is simple: caffeine was non-significant across all three model specifications. The coefficient was approximately negative 0.001 with p-values above 0.1 in every model. The overall model fit was very low — R-squared between 0.015 and 0.052 — meaning our full set of predictors explains essentially nothing about cross-country variation in depression prevalence.
This is consistent with what the EDA showed. The caffeine-depression correlation was weak and inconsistent across years from the start.

[SLIDE: Diagnostics + Sensitivity]
JOHN:
On the model quality side: all variance inflation factors were below 1.5, so there are no multicollinearity concerns. The residual diagnostics for the mortality model show reasonably well-behaved residuals with no severe heteroscedasticity. The Q-Q plot shows mild tail departures, likely driven by a handful of high-mortality outlier countries. The depression residuals are similarly clean.
For sensitivity: we varied the caffeine conversion factors by plus and minus 25% and re-ran the fully adjusted model under each scenario. The coefficients were perfectly stable. This is actually expected — because we z-score the predictor before regression, a uniform linear rescaling of the caffeine values doesn't change the standardized coefficient. What this tells us is that our conclusions don't depend on the specific caffeine-per-kilogram conversion number we chose. They do still depend on whether the relative ranking of countries by caffeine intake is approximately right.

[SLIDE: Limitations]
ALI:
A few things to be explicit about.
First, ecological fallacy. We're analyzing country-level aggregates. Even if we found a significant caffeine-mortality association after full adjustment, that would tell us nothing about what happens to an individual who drinks more coffee. Those are different questions and our design can't answer the individual-level one.
Second, our caffeine exposure is approximate. Caffeine per gram varies substantially by preparation method, roast, and product. We used fixed conversion factors applied uniformly across all countries, which is a real limitation.
Third, our coffee and tea inputs are single cross-sections applied to a multi-year panel. We're using 2022 and 2023 consumption figures to explain health outcomes in earlier years. That temporal mismatch matters.
Fourth, IHME GBD estimates are model-derived and less reliable for lower-income countries — which are also the lower-caffeine countries. This asymmetry could artificially strengthen our observed associations.

[SLIDE: Ethics]
ALI:
A few ethical notes. Caffeine consumption is deeply tied to culture — tea ceremonies in East Asia, coffee culture in Scandinavia, qahwa in the Middle East and Turkey. Framing any observed pattern as better or worse based on caffeine source or quantity would be culturally reductive. We've been careful to frame this as describing co-variation, not making prescriptions.
There's also a misuse risk. Ecological findings like these can be selectively cited by the beverage industry. We want to be clear: this is observational, country-level data. No causal claims are warranted.

[SLIDE: Conclusions]
ALI:
So what did we find?
Country-level caffeine consumption shows a negative association with all-cause mortality that is largely — but not entirely — explained by economic development. After fully adjusting for GDP, smoking, and alcohol, the caffeine-mortality coefficient attenuated by about 65% and landed at a p-value of 0.057. GDP is clearly the dominant driver. Whether the residual caffeine signal is real or reflects unmeasured confounding is something this design can't resolve.
For depression: caffeine is not meaningfully associated with cross-country variation in depression prevalence. Our predictors collectively explained almost nothing there, which suggests depression is driven by factors our dataset doesn't capture well.
The sensitivity analysis was reassuring — results don't depend on our specific conversion factor assumptions. And the broader finding lines up in direction with prior individual-level literature, even if our ecological design can't tell us why.
If this work continued, the natural next steps would be year-matched beverage consumption data, country fixed-effects models, and adding energy drink market share, which we couldn't get at the resolution we needed.
Thanks for watching.
